<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="6bca07c8-a2ee-5158-9405-9f9ede835692" activityNameId="24c3ae2c-f678-4daa-a216-fb650e98e102" parentActivityId="7aedd13e-cd86-5023-ac26-c0b604e7279c" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">sweet corn production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Zea mays L., corn</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">This activity starts with soil cultivation after the harvest of the previous crop.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This dataset includes cultivation of the field prior to planting, field treatments, planting, applications of nutrients and pesticides, and harvest. It ends with harvested sweet corn at the farm gate, prior to storage.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of Sweet Corn (fresh matter) in the US state of Florida  at farm, with an at harvest moisture content of 76.%. This dataset includes cultivation of the field prior to planting, field treatments, planting, applications of nutrients and pesticides, and harvest. Residues are not collected but remain on the field post-harvest and overwinter.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The average yield of Sweet Corn grown in Florida for the 2014-2021 seasons was 14,104 kg/ha (wet mass) (USDA NASS (2022a)).  The dataset reflects the average Sweet Corn produced in Florida from 2014 to 2021, inclusive, as that period allows for at least one value from USDA statistics for most parameters and generally three or more.  Seed establishment and weed control for sweet corn generally require tillage (EPA 2022; IPM 2003, IPM 1997), so this dataset reflects sweet corn production using conventional tillage practices (0% no till, 0% reduced till, 100% conventional tillage) (EPA 2022; IPM center 2003; IPM center 1997 data) and being grown in rotations with other vegetable crops. While genetically engineered sweet (fresh) corn seed is available, the share of sweet (fresh) corn grown from genetically engineered seed is not compiled; it is estimated that between 75 and 90% of North American sweet corn is conventional (USDA 2018b).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Area, productivity, use of mineral and organic fertilisers and pesticides, and irrigation inputs are based on farmer data reported to the U.S. Department of Agriculture where possible or budgets available for the state, unless otherwise noted. USDA NASS does not include fertilizer application data for Florida, so this dataset uses calculated values based on nutrient uptake rates. USDA NASS withholds pesticide application data for Florida, so this dataset uses estimated values based on other states and Florida guidance. Field operations and equipment types and fuel use are based on materials provided to growers by the agricultural extension office(s), including farm budgets, and on survey information agricultural extension office(s) collect from growers, in conjunction with row spacing data from USDA.  8.3% of crop land has installed drainage (tile or ditch), based on state-level agricultural survey data from USDA.  Irrigation is included based on share of crop irrigated (56.7% over the time period, USDA NASS (2018d)).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Total cropland land use, for all crops, in Florida decreased by 4% between 1997 and 2017 (NRCS 2020); USDA NASS does not report cropped area for Sweet Corn prior to 2016. The ecoinvent practice and associated crop LCI tool allocate land use change to all crops and activities that grew in the last 20 years in the US, and only to them, according to their respective area increase; crops for which planted area decreased are not attributed LUC impacts or credits. Thus, the amount of Land use change, annual crop is close to zero for Sweet Corn grown in Florida.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Soil characteristics, including pH, are based on distribution of soil pH sampling results reported in the 2020 Soil Test Summary (Bruulsema and Jones 2021). The share of acidic soils is likely overestimated as more frequent testing is to be expected on soils having needed lime and thus low pH soils are likely to be more represented amongst the collected samples. No anti-erosion practices are assumed in the dataset; instead, the erosion soil loss reported in the U.S. Natural Resources Conservation Service's Natural Resource Inventory is used.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">USDA NASS (2022a) Area, Production, Yield by State - Sweet Corn - 2016-2022. US Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agricultural Statistics Service. https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov (direct query: https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov/results/5E5B411A-F9EF-3B83-AAFF-995DD89820FC)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">USDA NASS (2018b) Statistical Methodology Name of Survey: Agricultural Resource Management Survey (ARMS) Phase II: PeanutProduction Practices Report, CornProduction Practices Report, and Soybean Production Practices Cost Report. US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://www.nass.usda.gov/Surveys/Guide_to_NASS_Surveys/Chemical_Use/2018_Peanuts_Soybeans_Corn/Statistical%20Methodology%202018.pdf</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">IPM center (1997) Crop Profile for Corn (Sweet) in Maryland. Southern Integrated Pest Management Center. https://ipmdata.ipmcenters.org/documents/cropprofiles/MDcorn-sweet.pdf</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">IPM center (2003) Crop Profile for Sweet Corn in the North Central United States. Southern Integrated Pest Management Center.Southern Integrated Pest Management Center. https://ipmdata.ipmcenters.org/documents/cropprofiles/us-ncr-sweetcorn.pdf</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">EPA (2022) Assessment of the Benefits of Atrazine and the Impacts of Potential Mitigation for Field Corn, Sweet Corn, Sorghum, and Sugarcane; PC Code (080803). (MEMORANDUM).US Environmental Protection Agency. https://downloads.regulations.gov/EPA-HQ-OPP-2013-0266-1624/content.pdf</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">USDA NASS (2018d) 2018 Irrigation and Water Management Survey  (2017 Census of Agriculture).US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://www.nass.usda.gov/Publications/AgCensus/2017/Online_Resources/Farm_and_Ranch_Irrigation_Survey/index.php</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">NRCS (2020) Land Cover/use of non-Federal rural land, by State and year, in the 2017 National Resources Inventory. USDA, Natural Resources Conservation Service. http://www.nrcs.usda.gov/Internet/NRCS_RCA/reports/nri_crop_nat.html, https://www.nrcs.usda.gov/wps/portal/nrcs/rca/national/technical/nra/rca/text/#NRI%20Cropland</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13">Bruulsema and Jones 2021. Soil Test Summary 2020. Foundation for Agronomic Research and Plant Nutrition Canada present this 2020 summary of soil test levels in North America. Foundation for Agronomic Research, Plant Nutrition Canada. https://soiltest.tfi.org/about/about_soil_test_summaryaccessed August 30, 2021</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="e2e1f67d-3393-4182-86f6-1ada2f77c3e5">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">0111:Growing of cereals (except rice), leguminous crops and oil seeds</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="8dbe7fbe-7375-4cb0-a1a2-6d55bc55e86e">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">US-FL</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Production of Sweet Corn in Florida (US-FL).</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset reflects current practice for Sweet Corn in Florida as of 2022.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2014-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The valid period covers  2014-01-01 through 2021-12-31 based on primary data sources.  The production volumes, areas and applications are covered by data throughout the time period (annual for production and area, alternate years for applications). Because the specific pesticides used show time-dependent trends, the most recent 2 years of data are used to avoid underweighting the most dominant pesticides currently used and to avoid skewing  impacts based on compounds no longer in use. Field operations are based on enterprise crop budgets and other guidance and change little year to year.  Detailed guidance or enterprise crop budgets are not available for Florida sweet corn, so this dataset assumed field operations as detail in the enterprise crop budget for sweet corn from Clemson Extension (2020). The data presented here is aligned with Florida guidance from 2002 and 1997 and thus assumed valid for the dataset.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
