      <intermediateExchange id="ee4f9c1b-f6c7-55bd-9c47-f2494e0802fa" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" amount="6.86701986754967E-05" intermediateExchangeId="1be4f7e4-5244-4f9d-b80d-7fbf1e337e2b" activityLinkId="110a25f4-4a5e-5b5d-a1b3-818843c1f428">
        <name xml:lang="en">[thio]carbamate-compound</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">This exchange is an aggregate of proxies for applied pesticide(s) Methomyl, Mancozeb (2.734E-1 kg/ha {1,2,2,1,1}; 6.952E-1 kg/ha {1,2,2,1,1}, respectively).
Because all pesticide data is withheld in NASS (denoted as "D" in the data, indicating a non-zero value withheld to preserve confidentiality), pesticide applications for Florida are extrapolated from Clemson Extension guidance for South Carolina (Clemson 2020). These values were compared to crop profile and IPM guidance information for Florida (Kanissery et al 2022, IPM 2002).

Sources: 
Clemson Extension (2020) Sweetcorn - For roadside or local market. Cooperative Extension Service, Clemson University. 
IPM (2002) Crop Profile for Corn (Sweet) in Florida. Integrated Pest Management. https://ipmdata.ipmcenters.org/documents/cropprofiles/FLSweetcorn2002.pdf
Kanissery et al. (2022) CHAPTER 17. SWEET CORN PRODUCTION. University of Florida's Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences. https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/publication/cv135</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <normal meanValue="6.86701986754967E-05" variance="4.3468994972097E-11" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="4.3468994972097E-11"/>
