      <intermediateExchange id="5cd78449-c2cd-50c6-b421-64fa7601d4c4" unitId="86bbe475-8a8f-44d8-914c-e398787e7121" amount="7.09017615033353E-05" intermediateExchangeId="609a0500-990a-53fb-b8be-27e8fae955cb" activityLinkId="78b6d553-b8a1-5a09-ae51-28a3b7bb7355">
        <name xml:lang="en">harvesting, by sweet corn picker</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">ha</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">7.09E-5 ha/kg harvesting, by sweet corn picker (1. effective pass(es) per year). 
 Detailed guidance or enterprise crop budgets are not available for Florida sweet corn, so this dataset assumed field operations as detail in the enterprise crop budget for sweet corn from Clemson Extension (2020). The data presented here is aligned with Florida guidance from 2002 and 1997 and thus assumed valid for the dataset.Field operations are as identified in crop- and rotation-specific enterprise crop budgets supplied by the regional agricultural extension office and matched to equipment type in the budget or crop guidance unless otherwise noted. Operations are matched to equipment type and where multiple options are available, the share of each is determined from guidance and annual farmer survey data (Custom Rate Summaries) for contracted operations/equipment. Field cultivation and tillage operations are specific to the tillage regime used. Seed establishment and weed control for sweet corn generally require tillage (EPA 2022; IPM 2003, IPM 1997), so this dataset reflects sweet corn production using conventional tillage practices (0% reduced till, 100% conventional tillage, and 0% no till, ). 
Sources:
Clemson Extension 2020, Kanissery et al 2022, Liu et al 2022b, Hanna, Mark 2016, Schuler and Frank 1998, Lattz and Schnitkey 2021b; Clemson Extension (2020) Sweetcorn - For roadside or local market. Cooperative Extension Service, Clemson University. , Kanissery et al. (2022) CHAPTER 17. SWEET CORN PRODUCTION. University of Florida's Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences. https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/publication/cv135, Liu et al (2022b) CHAPTER 2. FERTILIZER MANAGEMENT FOR VEGETABLE PRODUCTION IN FLORIDA. University of Florida's Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences. https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/publication/cv296, Hanna, Mark (2016) Estimating the Field Capacity of Farm Machines. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/pdf/a3-24.pdf, Schuler and Frank (1998) A3510 Estimating Agricultural Field Machinery Costs. University of Wisconsin-Extension. https://learningstore.uwex.edu/Assets/pdfs/A3510.pdf, Lattz and Schnitkey (2021b) Machinery Cost Estimates: Field Operations. Department of Agricultural and Consumer Economics, University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. https://farmdoc.illinois.edu/assets/management/machinery-costs/field_operations.pdf; EPA (2022) Assessment of the Benefits of Atrazine and the Impacts of Potential Mitigation for Field Corn, Sweet Corn, Sorghum, and Sugarcane; PC Code (080803). (MEMORANDUM).US Environmental Protection Agency. https://downloads.regulations.gov/EPA-HQ-OPP-2013-0266-1624/content.pdf ; IPM center (2003) Crop Profile for Sweet Corn in the North Central United States. Southern Integrated Pest Management Center.Southern Integrated Pest Management Center. https://ipmdata.ipmcenters.org/documents/cropprofiles/us-ncr-sweetcorn.pdf ; IPM center (1997) Crop Profile for Corn (Sweet) in Maryland. Southern Integrated Pest Management Center. https://ipmdata.ipmcenters.org/documents/cropprofiles/MDcorn-sweet.pdf</comment>
